I actually sat down and figured out the whole process because I am a total nerd for engineering.

You'dthis.

Warning:detected.


Basically, this combines some tricks they use for drilling into ice in Antarctica, where water can re-freeze in seconds, others they use for drilling oil wells and tunnels into hard but unstable rock, and some standard pier construction methods.

This assumes they've figured out that water reverts when separated from the anomaly, and that it's probably related to the thing they can see a couple meters under the surface. From there, what you do is:

Helicopter in a small heavy-duty drilling rig. (These do actually exist. They have mining, quarrying, and construction applications.)
Mount rig on a flat barge and drag to just above the anomaly under the lake.
Drill set of small bore holes through lake around anomaly; hammer in anchor piles.

this assumes  has occurred to them
As with arctic drilling, the neat part is that the  and wreak havoc on your machinery.


Drill a pilot hole to just above Sun Wukong, and line the whole thing with pipe as you go to keep your hole open.
switch to large tunnel-boring bit. Using the first pipe as a guide, expand the hole and insert utility pipe sections. At the end, you have a roughly 2.25 meter hole lined with pipe above the anomaly, preferably big enough for a reseus macaque and a large chunk of iron-water to fit through. Cap this with a watertight seal. Last thing you need is a freak rainstorm refilling a week's worth of drilling.
Drill a second hole like this, but at an angle landing it a safe distance underneath SW.
Now comes the tricky part. Carefully drill a series of holes around SW, connecting the upper and lower tunnels.
Ream out the area between these holes, and gradually build a complete watertight connection between the upper and lower tunnels, leaving only a thin link of Iron-water between the rest of the lake and the now isolated chunk around SW.
Run a final check that your anchor columns are up to the job of supporting your construction project in normal water. You're starting over if you get this wrong.
sever the connection between the chunk and the lake.
Slam a plug into the hole to keep the water from flooding in faster than you can pull the now-free chunk out of the tunnel and onto the barge.
Get it to shore, and as far from the water as you can.
Proceed with archeology, discover it turns off when less than 20 liters of water are present.









